IMPORTANT:

If you are a family with students in grades 5 -12 that are in need of a Chromebook (your student should have kept their device over the summer and should bring it to school on the first day , 9/14.) We will be providing three successive days for pickup of devices. If you are a family with a student K - 4, they will receive your device on the first day of school when you meet your teacher.

If you are a remote (distance learning family/student) that needs a device, you can come at this time to receive your student device.

LOCATION - Pull up to the ES Auditorium foyer (in the back of the school) We will come to you and discuss your student, need and provide you with a device.

TIME/ DATE:

Wednesday 9/9 - 4 - 6 PM
Thursday 9/10 - 4 - 6 PM
Friday 9/11 - 4 - 6 PM

If you are unable to make these times or don't have transportation, please let the IT department know and we will coordinate a time with you.

If you have any questions, concerns or need please call 315-497-2670 ext. 1218
or email John Owen at jowen@moraviaschool.org

Thank you for flexibility and support!

The IT department is looking to support the school community that is either going remote and needs a device and/or needs internet connectivity support.

ATTENTION - K - 4 Parents

The Technology department is asking families to return iPads and chargers if your student was in kindergarten to 3rd grade last year.

The drop off will be tomorrow, Friday, August 21st from 10 am to 4 pm and Monday, August 24th from 12 pm to 6 pm.

We are asking parents to come to the 5th grade driveway (this is the pull up next to the main driveway at the elementary school). A staff member will meet you at your vehicle and take your device and charger and note your name for returning the device. The Technology department will be updating the devices to get them ready for the first day of school.

We understand that some families may not be able to make this time. If that is the case, please reach out to the building and we will coordinate a time for you to drop off your child’s iPad. If you have any questions or concerns, please contact the elementary school and John Owen, Director of Technology will get back to you as soon as possible.

Thank you in advance, we appreciate your flexibility and look forward to seeing you all over the next few days.

post_text:
Tomorrow, Friday, June 26th, the Moravia Central School District will be holding graduation for the class of 2020. Around 6PM, buses will be bringing the students to the venue. We invite the community to wave to the students and cheer them on for a mini parade while abiding by social distancing rules. The buses will leave the elementary school, head onto Main Street, up Church Street and finish on Park Street. We are aware the map said Congress, this is not the case. The parade will include CHURCH street!

The banners that were hung up through out the village will be on the outside of the buses to show which students are on which buses, they will then be handed to the graduating seniors following the graduation ceremony. At this time, only graduates and their guests are allowed to attend graduation. If you would like to watch the ceremony, the district will be live streaming the graduation on Facebook.

post_text:
Lip Sync 2020: During this time of distant learning, some staff at Millard Fillmore Elementary School wanted to let their students know that they are always here for their students. They miss them all so much!

The song “Ain’t No Mountain High Enough” was written by Nickolas Ashford and Valerie Simpson in 1966, inspired by a walk through Central Park and their ambition to become a part of Motown Records. It was originally recorded by Marvin Gaye and Tammi Terrell.

Check out the Motown Records website for more information on Marvin Gaye, Tammi Terrell, and other artists from the 1960’s through today.

The song “Ain’t No Mountain High Enough” was written by Nickolas Ashford and Valerie Simpson in 1966, inspired by a walk through Central Park and their ambition to become a part of Motown Records. It was originally recorded by Marvin Gaye and Tammi Terrell.

Check out the Motown Records website for more information on Marvin Gaye, Tammi Terrell, and other artists from the 1960’s through today.

IMPORTANT INFORMATION REGARDING BUDGET VOTES: Governor Cuomo signed Executive Order 202.39 extending the timeline for receipt of absentee ballots. School districts must now accept ballots sent via U.S. mail until Tuesday, June 16. The cutoff for hand-delivered ballots remains at 5 p.m. tomorrow (Tuesday, June 9). A Ballot Box has been placed in the north parking lot until 5 p.m. on Tuesday, June 9. After June 9th, all ballots must be received by mail only.

The ballots will be counted by Board of Education approved Election Inspectors after 5 pm on June 16.

post_text: We are in the last week of May which means the final art challenge of the month! The art department was ecstatic to see how many students went outside last week to create beautiful chalk art, so we decided to give you another challenge that allows you to go outside again and take advantage of the nice weather! For this week's challenge, the art department is asking you all to create self portraits made out of material found from nature! You have a week to complete this optional challenge (May 25th - May 29th). When completing the challenge, make sure you take a "birds eye view" photo of your self portrait and send it to either Mrs. Hatfield, Mr. Welgoss, or Miss. Haessner.

For this week's challenge, the art department is asking you all to create interactive chalk! You have a week to complete this optional challenge (May 18th - May 22nd). When completing the challenge, make sure you take a "birds eye view" photo of you you in your chalk environment and send it to either Mrs. Hatfield, Mr. Welgoss, or Miss. Haessner.

Applications for military ballots may be obtained from the District Clerk’s Office at 315-497-2670, x2003 or email at aburhans@moraviaschool.org and the military voter may designate a preference to receive the application by mail, fax or email. post_text:
Parents, Alumni, Community Members and Friends of the Moravia class of 2020

This afternoon there will be a parade of vehicles lining up on West Cayuga Street behind emergency vehicles in order to parade past the high school in honor of our Senior Class of 2020. The Seniors will be standing on the front lawn of the school and will be looking forward to your support. Please honk your horns and wave at our graduates as you drive past, showing your love and support. The parade will begin at 5:00, so please line up prior to that or drive past the high school around that time.

Show them your Moravia Blue Devil Pride!

Any seniors who would like to take their picture in front of their signs may do so PRIOR to 3:30. Please maintain proper social distancing and DO NOT remove your sign until after the parade.

It is upon us, the latest challenge! It's the one everyone has been waiting for, it's Music Week!

Here are the days:

Monday: Music Monday: Play or sing your favorite song!

Tuesday: Tune In Tuesday: Listen to music that helps you work!

Wednesday: Rocker Wednesday- dress up as your favorite musician

Thursday: Ensemble Thursday: make an instrument with objects around your house, or make a band with your family.

Friday: Funky Friday Dance Party

Please post your pics with the #mcsdmusicweek You can also email your pics to John Owen, Carrie Love, and/or the music department. We'll place them into a video each night! Thanks for participating!

This morning we bagged up a week's worth of breakfast and lunches (1,030 breakfasts and 1,030 lunches) for 206 Moravia students. They will be delivered on Monday.

Moravia CSD and Food Services Director Jen Parker-Smith would like to give a huge shout out to all of the volunteers who have helped and also to Moravia's Kinney Drugs who has generously donated all the paper bags.

Thank you Moravia community!

post_text:
Update from the Moravia Youth League baseball:

Fundraiser update:

After speaking to the Cherrydale Rep. we are still good to sell until Friday, April 3rd. After Friday we have 2 options to get our orders in.

1. Enter orders online using your credit card.
2. Meet Danielle Proper at Kinneys parking lot to place your envelope in a box on Saturday, April 4th from 9 - 10.
*if you would/could write a check for the cash you have collected we would appreciate it.
All items will be shipped to the ball players house. If entering online you will need to type in your address. If you are to drop your envelope off you need to include a piece of paper with your address, please.

Thank you and stay well!

If you should have any questions call Danielle at 315-730-8745.

post_text: Our students are doing some pretty cool things! Upon completion of their electricity units, the physics students programmed and built Makey Makey devices. A Makey Makey is a device that takes normal objects such as paper, water, gummi bears and play-doh and connects them to your computer. Some of the devices made were a game controller for Tetris, a random name generator, a water piano, a pencil and paper piano, a gummi bear emoji keyboard and a life size game controller.

post_text: 7th grade students in Ms. Thibodeau's class have been thinking a lot about nutrition as part of their Mars unit. This week they made chocolate chip cookies with both quinoa flour and cricket powder. Both ingredients offer a complete source of protein because they contain the 9 essential amino acids needed for human health and survival. Students are following this up with calculations to determine the nutritional value of their cookies. We have some healthy astronauts in the making!

post_text:
Learning all about the heart! Students at Millard Fillmore Elementary School had their "Kids Heart Challenge" assembly today. It's all part of the Heart Challenge fundraiser that helps raise money for the American Heart Association. The money raised helps support kids, schools and physical education by teaching heart health, eating healthy and character education. Last year, the school was #1 in fundraising out of four counties! Let's see if we can beat last years totals!

Our students learned how often you should be exercising, what they should be eating as well as some fun ways to jump rope! What a fun way to learn more about the heart!

The MCS Music Boosters Club will be hosting a “Father-Daughter Dance” at the Elementary School Gymnasium on Saturday January 25 from 6:30-8:30pm. The event is a fundraiser for the MCS Music Program. Tickets are $5 each and will be available from Jennings Department Store and Ms. Fland at the Elementary School beginning mid-January. Any unsold tickets will also be available at the door. There will be music for dancing, snacks and beverages
available for sale, a photo station and family friendly activities. Girls may bring their father or any special adult in their lives with them to this gala event. Get dressed up and bring your favorite princess out for a charming night of dancing and fun.

post_text: This morning the female a cappella group from SUNY Potsdam known as A Sharp Arrangement came to perform for many of Moravia's singers. Students in grades 6th-12th chorus got the opportunity to watch their performance which featured many contemporary a cappella songs. Following the performance the High School Choralaires participated in a workshop with the girls from the group. Students divided up into sections to learn the song "Light On" and then came together as a group to perform with the college students. It was an engaging and positive experience for all students involved.

post_text: Our 6th graders stepped into the OR to prepare some “patients” for the afterlife! Students learned about the mummification process and the cultural reasons the Egyptians performed it. They then had to use the knowledge to perform surgery to mummify their patients. What a fun and unique way to learn!

post_text:
In order to learn about celebrating different cultures and welcoming everyone, Ms Moraghan's 2nd grade had a wonderful feast on Tuesday. Please read her account:

Today was tamale Tuesday in my classroom! We learned that different cultures have different food traditions for the holidays. In the beginning of the year we welcomed a new student that only spoke Spanish and we felt it would be great to try something new and bring some of his traditions to our room! The joy and excitement had by him and the rest of my classroom was a great way to go into Thanksgiving break!

Showing off their talent! This weekend the Moravia Drama Club performed "Once on this Island." The musical tells the story of a young peasant girl, named Ti Moune, who is saved by four island gods, and is forced to make a journey to pursue her love of a wealthy islander.

A great job by all cast and crew on a wonderful performance.

post_text:
From Nov. 4th through November 20th, all Millard Fillmore elementary students will be bringing home a fundraiser packet with a sample of the book in it. These sample books, must be returned to your teacher, unless purchased.

The Save Around coupon book fundraiser is a great way to raise funds for our school AND save families money! We have many new local eateries included this year, and the Cortland/Ithaca edition is now only $20!

This fundraiser is to provide funding to support the elementary school’s PBIS committee. The funding will bring FUN programs to our school!

By working together, we can raise extra money to do some extra cool stuff here at Millard Fillmore Elementary! Examples are guest speakers, musical guests, and other awesome programs for our students!

Thank you for your continued support!

post_text: Learning all about El Día de los Muertos, or Day of the Dead. The holiday is dedicated to honoring and remembering loved ones who have passed away. While the day is celebrated in many countries, students in Mrs. Stoyell's 7th grade class focused on traditions in Mexico. They made sugar skulls, pan de Muerto, and other authentic symbols to decorate ofrendas, or offerings. What a great way for students to learn about other cultures!

post_text:
Moravia Middle School presents Fiddler on the Roof Jr!
Come see if the town of Anatevka can hold on to its traditions in this Tony Award-winning Broadway musical.

Show nights are November 15th at 7:00 pm and November 16th at 4:00 pm. Tickets are $5 pre-sale and $6 at the door.

Tickets are available at https://www.showtix4u.com/event-details/35914

Set in the little village of Anatevka, Fiddler on the Roof JR. follows Tevye the milkman as he tries to protect his daughters and his way of life from a changing world. With the help of a colorful and tight-knit Jewish community, Tevye tries to marry off his daughters and instill in them a sense of tradition in the face of growing anti-Semitism in Czarist Russia.

post_text: Spending Halloween at Casowasco Retreat Center! 6th graders spent the day doing a variety of team building activities. These activities were directly connected to an ELA unit using the books Wonder and Auggie and Me and support our year-long theme of identity. At the end of the day students also worked on figuring out positive steps they can personally take to make the school a kinder place. They ended the day with a party and celebrated their hard work!

post_text: Learning a new skill! Tandy Leather visited our 4th graders at Millard Fillmore Elementary to show them different products made from animal skins. They were also taught about the leather making/tanning process and even got to create their own stamped leather bookmark! This visit ties in directly to the 4th grade Social Studies curriculum which has students learning about how where they live affects their lifestyle, Native American culture and using natural resources to meet needs.

post_text: Learning that science can be fun! This week Mrs. Genson, Mrs. Johnson and Ms. Hess and their 3rd grade classes visited the Science Center in Ithaca. The students learned about wind turbines and even got the chance to build their own! Their goal was to create a wind turbine that, when placed in front of a fan, would spin around. If it didn't work, they went back to the drawing board and worked together to come up with a solution to get their turbine to spin. A great show of teamwork and hard work, all while having fun!

On Wednesday, 10/9 several 9th graders attended the first ever how will you.... E.A.T. (Environmental, Agriculture, Technology) Your Future? day. This was an interactive Career Day which allowed the students to spend time at Dickman Farms, Oakwood dairy, and Cayuga Milk Ingredients. Students engaged in hands on learning stations that connected students to STEM skills that exist in the world of Agriculture.

Here's a wonderful write up - https://auburnpub.com/lifestyles/entering-the-field-cayuga-county-area-students-attend-agriculture-career/article_f5e87ba1-cb17-5f56-ba5b-8d94908e2350.html#tracking-source=home-top-story-1
